  "Idea": "We propose MetaGeom-BnB: a meta-learned, geometry-aware branch-and-bound algorithm that dynamically optimizes both variable branching and SDP relaxation enhancement through an online-learned policy, significantly accelerating convergence to exact solutions in combinatorial optimization. While the prior art leverages instantaneous Riemannian geometry for branching decisions, MetaGeom-BnB introduces a closed-loop learning framework that observes the evolution of the relaxation gap, dual residuals, and spectral properties across the BnB tree and learns to predict the most effective actions—i.e., which variable to branch on and what type of local constraint (e.g., eigenvector cut, trace regularization, or diagonal dominance lift) to apply—to maximally reduce the duality gap. At each node, after solving the enhanced SDP, the algorithm encodes the current state (primal/dual matrices, constraint graph, gap history) into a heterogeneous graph where variables, constraints, and dual slacks are nodes and edges. A lightweight graph neural network (GNN), trained via reinforcement learning with a reward based on gap reduction per unit computational cost, predicts a probability distribution over candidate branching variables and enhancement operators. The top-ranked action is executed, and the resulting transition (state → action → new gap) is used to update the policy via proximal policy optimization (PPO). This enables the algorithm to discover non-obvious, high-leverage branching sequences and relaxation strategies that may not align with myopic geometric heuristics but lead to faster overall convergence. To ensure theoretical soundness, all enhancements maintain convexity and the lower bound remains valid; primal upper bounds are updated via randomized rounding. Warm-starting and extrapolation from learned gap decay trends further accelerate convergence. The method is particularly powerful in structured domains such as MAX-k-CUT, integer quadratic programs, and formal verification of deep ReLU networks, where subproblem similarity allows the GNN to generalize across nodes and even across problem instances. By fusing geometric insight with meta-learning, MetaGeom-BnB shifts the paradigm from hand-designed, static branching rules to adaptive, experience-driven search control—offering a scalable, intelligent alternative to both classical BnB and pure geometric methods.",
